    <item>
      <title>Tyler’s Law: After losing her 19-year-old son to a fentanyl overdose, Juli Shamash is lobbying for legislation in his name</title>
      <author>Jesse Rifkin       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/499/2025-05-07_tylers-law-after-losing-her-19-year-old-son-to-a-fentanyl-overdose-juli-shamash-is-lobbying-for-legislation-in-his-name</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/499/2025-05-07_tylers-law-after-losing-her-19-year-old-son-to-a-fentanyl-overdose-juli-shamash-is-lobbying-for-legislation-in-his-name</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 07 May 2025 18:18:55 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The best way to learn about how a bill actually becomes a law is to talk to the real people working behind the scenes for them. When this GovTrack user wrote to us about a bill she has been advocating for, we wanted to know more.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I would like for my son’s legacy to be saving people,” &lt;a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/juli-shamash-62733112/"&gt;Juli Shamash&lt;/a&gt; says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After losing her 19-year-old son Tyler to a fatal fentanyl overdose in 2018, , she advocated for enacting legislation called Tyler’s Law in states and Congress. But although most states which enacted it so far have done so unanimously, Congress has thrown some unexpected roadblocks her way.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I knew all the ‘mom’ stuff,” Shamash says, speaking to GovTrack in a Zoom interview, “but I knew nothing about the political process other than what I remembered from &lt;em&gt;Schoolhouse Rock&lt;/em&gt;.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,"&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;The state level&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;When Tyler overdosed, the “standard” hospital emergency room drug test checked for several substances including cocaine, heroin, and amphetamines – though not fentanyl. His family, including mother Juli, didn’t even know fentanyl was in his system until the coroner’s toxicology report came back a full five months later.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Juli began pushing for a law in her home state of California, requiring hospitals to test for fentanyl too. While some already did voluntarily, it wasn’t actually mandated.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The bill proved to be noncontroversial. In 2022, &lt;a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billVotesClient.xhtml?bill_id=202120220SB864"&gt;the California Assembly and state Senate both passed it unanimously&lt;/a&gt;. Governor Gavin Newsom (D) signed it into law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then in 2023, Maryland enacted the Josh Siems Act, named after a &lt;a href="https://elm.umaryland.edu/announcements/2023/The-UMB-Pulse-Podcast-The-Josh-Siems-Act.php"&gt;31-year-old Maryland man&lt;/a&gt; who also died of a fentanyl overdose. Same &lt;a href="https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/2023RS/votes/house/0525.pdf"&gt;unanimous&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/2023RS/votes/senate/0918.pdf"&gt;votes&lt;/a&gt; as in California. Gov. Wes Moore (D) signed it into law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Though she lived 3,000 miles away, Shamash &lt;a href="https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/cmte_testimony/2023/hgo/1oDwXnGYFGyHGeJUcT6GqNly6omHX3cTw.pdf"&gt;testified before the Maryland legislature&lt;/a&gt;, calling it “a commonsense measure” before adding “I can personally speak to the fact that this bill has the potential to save lives.” Of the people who testified before the Maryland Health and Government Operations Committee, &lt;a href="https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Legislation/WitnessSignup/HB0811?ys=2023RS"&gt;&lt;em&gt;everyone&lt;/em&gt; spoke in favor&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Since then, several more states have enacted similar legislation, most similarly named after local people who died from fentanyl overdoses:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Virginia enacted Malcolm’s Law, named after &lt;a href="https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/gov-youngkin-signs-malcoms-law-in-honor-of-virginia-teen-lost-to-fentanyl/3877231/"&gt;17-year-old Malcolm Kent&lt;/a&gt;, also &lt;a href="https://lis.virginia.gov/vote-details/HB2742/20251/2518375"&gt;passing&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://lis.virginia.gov/vote-details/HB2742/20251/SV593"&gt;unanimously&lt;/a&gt;. Virginia Gov. Glenn Youngkin (R) signed it into law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Florida’s state legislature passed &lt;a href="https://www.flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2025/1195/BillText/er/PDF"&gt;Gage’s Law&lt;/a&gt;, named after &lt;a href="https://floridapolitics.com/archives/732838-gages-law-mandating-fentanyl-testing-ready-for-governors-signature/#:~:text=The%20bill%20would%20require%20health,testing%20would%20further%20be%20required."&gt;29-year-old Gage Taylor&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2025/1195/Vote/HouseVote_h01195c1092.PDF"&gt;also&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2025/1195/Vote/SenateVote_h01195c1012.PDF"&gt;unanimously&lt;/a&gt;. As of this writing, it &lt;a href="https://www.clickorlando.com/news/florida/2025/04/19/florida-gov-ron-desantis-signs-4-bills-into-law-heres-when-they-take-effect/"&gt;awaits a potential signature from Gov. Ron DeSantis (R)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pennsylvania’s law, not named after an individual, &lt;a href="https://www.legis.state.pa.us/CFDOCS/Legis/RC/Public/rc_view_byBill.cfm?sess_yr=2023&amp;amp;sess_ind=0&amp;amp;rc_body=S&amp;amp;bill_body=S&amp;amp;bill_type=B&amp;amp;bill_nbr=683&amp;amp;bhDate=12/13/2023"&gt;passed the state Senate unanimously&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.legis.state.pa.us/CFDOCS/Legis/RC/Public/rc_view_byBill.cfm?sess_yr=2023&amp;amp;sess_ind=0&amp;amp;rc_body=H&amp;amp;bill_body=S&amp;amp;bill_type=B&amp;amp;bill_nbr=683&amp;amp;bhDate=12/13/2023"&gt;the state House 166-37&lt;/a&gt;. (Read on to see the causes of the holdouts’ opposition.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,"&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;The federal level: 2023-24&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Shamash partnered with several other mothers who lost children (mostly sons) to fentanyl overdoses. Thurraya Kent from Virginia lost her son Malcolm, while Perla Mendoza from California lost her son Eli and founded &lt;a href="https://projecteli.info/"&gt;Project Eli&lt;/a&gt; in response.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I am in awe of Juli because she has been able to harness her grief and continue this effort year after year with the hope of saving lives,” Kent told GovTrack by email. “Simultaneously, she has helped me and others who grieve to add purpose to our grief.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Together, the cadre of mothers helped get Tyler’s Law introduced in Congress for the first time in 2023. But first, they had to make some policy changes from the state-level versions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The federal bill tasks the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) with a study on how frequently hospitals &lt;em&gt;currently&lt;/em&gt; test for fentanyl for overdose patients. Based on the results of that study, the bill then requires HHS to issue non-binding guidance to hospitals on the issue.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It couldn’t be exactly the same as the bill I got passed in California,” Shamash admits. “Due to the &lt;a href="https://constitution.congress.gov/constitution/amendment-10/"&gt;10th Amendment&lt;/a&gt;, the federal government cannot order all hospitals to do something.” The 10th Amendment grants the powers not explicitly reserved to the federal government to the state governments instead.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Next up: attracting congressional cosponsors.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That part represented “a lot of hard work,” Shamash says. “First, contacting everyone on the Senate Health Committee, then everyone on House Energy and Commerce,” the two committees to which the bills were referred. “Then contacting everyone who &lt;em&gt;wasn’t&lt;/em&gt; on either of those committees, but had introduced fentanyl bills in the past.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“But I discovered: some members feel if it’s not someone from their district, it doesn’t matter to them,” Shamash reveals. “The most frustrating part is, when I called certain offices to ask for the [legislative] assistant’s name, they wouldn’t give it to me unless I was a constituent. Makes no sense because if the member is on the Health Committee, aren’t they supposed to be serving the whole country?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;(That’s a frustration GovTrack has heard from many users.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr6600"&gt;Rep. Ted Lieu (D-CA36)&lt;/a&gt; from Shamash’s home state introduced the House version, with an exactly evenly-bipartisan 48 cosponsors: &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr6600/cosponsors"&gt;24 Democrats and 24 Republicans&lt;/a&gt;. Then-Sen. Joe Manchin (I-WV), from one of the states hit hardest by the fentanyl crisis, introduced the Senate version with nine bipartisan cosponsors: &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s3519/cosponsors"&gt;five Democrats and four Republicans&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Despite those levels of cosponsorship, neither version received so much as a committee hearing nor a committee vote.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Some members discussed folding it in as a provision within the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr4531"&gt;Support for Patients and Communities Reauthorization Act&lt;/a&gt;, a larger bill dealing with opioid prevention, recovery, and treatment. At least according to Shamash’s version of events, the amendment was introduced too late to include.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Either way, it would have been a moot point: while &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2023/h715"&gt;the House overwhelmingly passed the larger bill 386-37&lt;/a&gt;, the Senate never took it up.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;The federal level: 2025&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;In March 2025, two new versions of Tyler’s Law were introduced. While Rep. Lieu once again took the lead for &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr2004"&gt;the House bill&lt;/a&gt;, with Sen. Manchin now retired, newly-elected freshman &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/jim_banks/412702"&gt;Sen. Jim Banks (R-IN)&lt;/a&gt; took over as the lead sponsor of &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s921"&gt;the Senate bill&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Interestingly, though Banks served as a House representative during the prior Congress, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr6600/cosponsors"&gt;he &lt;em&gt;didn’t&lt;/em&gt; cosponsor the prior House version&lt;/a&gt;. A staffer in his office told GovTrack he picked up the baton from his recently-retired predecessor, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/mike_braun/412839"&gt;Sen. Mike Braun&lt;/a&gt;, who cosponsored the prior Senate version.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It’s also an issue close to Sen. Banks’ heart. The &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?sponsor=412702#congress=119&amp;amp;sort=introduced_date"&gt;very first bill he ever introduced as a senator&lt;/a&gt; in January was the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s63"&gt;CBW Fentanyl Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would amend the &lt;a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/STATUTE-105/pdf/STATUTE-105-Pg647.pdf#page=76"&gt;Chemical and Biological Weapons Control and Warfare Elimination Act of 1991&lt;/a&gt; to include fentanyl as a biological weapon.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Yet the new Tyler’s Law faces a daunting setback: so far, both 2025 versions have accumulated &lt;em&gt;fewer&lt;/em&gt; cosponsors than their previous iterations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, some people retired or are no longer there,” Shamash explains. When GovTrack pointed out that some of the &lt;em&gt;prior&lt;/em&gt; version’s cosponsors are still serving yet aren’t cosponsoring the current version, Shamash suggests that they may have had staff turnover, with new employees not keeping their bosses apprised that the new version was even introduced.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There’s still time for cosponsors to sign on – perhaps as much as a year and eight months, if it takes until the end of the current two-year Congress.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Besides, cosponsorship level isn’t necessarily a reliable predictor of enactment. Some bills have become laws &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7888"&gt;despite&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr3746"&gt;having&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7938"&gt;zero&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s3285"&gt;cosponsors&lt;/a&gt;. Meanwhile, other bills have attracted more than half the House as cosponsors, yet nonetheless &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/363/2020-03-02_are-these-the-deals-congress-will-make-in-2020"&gt;failed to receive a vote&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;Amendment vote&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;On April 29, the House Energy and Commerce Committee &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/live/X7rdmmwvQiY?si=YyTfXPo2fKTmCDc9&amp;amp;t=12283"&gt;failed by a tied 24-24 vote&lt;/a&gt; to add Tyler’s Law as an amendment to the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr2483"&gt;SUPPORT for Patients and Communities Reauthorization Act&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Every Democrat voted in favor, while every Republican either voted against or didn’t vote, not because of the substance but because the policy hadn’t received a committee hearing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I heard my colleague say that he was looking to support amendments that were bipartisan, that were about substance abuse, that were our friends, our constituents, and our family members. Those were his words,” &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/nanette_barragan/412687"&gt;Rep. Nanette Barragán (D-CA44)&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/live/X7rdmmwvQiY?si=eKkuBgk-qzAZLJmA&amp;amp;t=12739"&gt;said in the committee hearing&lt;/a&gt;. “This is that amendment.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“While I support this policy, I must oppose this amendment because it did not receive proper committee consideration,” &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/robert_latta/412256"&gt;Rep. Bob Latta (R-OH5)&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/live/X7rdmmwvQiY?si=PqlaFkapAQG9PB48&amp;amp;t=13047"&gt;countered in that same committee hearing&lt;/a&gt;. However, “I believe this is a common-sense policy that could save lives.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;The name&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Federal laws are sometimes named after people whose life stories helped inspire them. By GovTrack’s count, two such laws have already been enacted in 2025.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Signed by President Joe Biden as &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?status=1,3&amp;amp;sort=-current_status_date#congress=118&amp;amp;current_status%5B%5D=28&amp;amp;sort=-introduced_date"&gt;one of the last new laws of his presidency&lt;/a&gt; and named after a young activist who died of brain cancer at age 10, the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h60"&gt;Gabriella Miller Kids First Research Act&lt;/a&gt; allocates federal funds for pediatric cancer research.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Signed into law by President Donald Trump as &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?status=1,3&amp;amp;sort=-current_status_date#current_status%5B%5D=28&amp;amp;sort=introduced_date"&gt;the very first new law of his second term&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s5"&gt;Laken Riley Act&lt;/a&gt; expands the government’s power to both detain and deport undocumented immigrants charged with certain crimes. It’s named after a 22-year-old University of Georgia student murdered by an undocumented Venezuelan immigrant who was &lt;a href="https://www.redandblack.com/athensnews/jose-ibarra-indicted-on-10-charges-in-laken-riley-homicide/article_729eb806-0e09-11ef-89a0-3f748efc672e.html"&gt;previously arrested but released&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Both laws include their namesake’s full name. So why name it Tyler’s Law, instead of the Tyler Shamash Law?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I would have to keep explaining how to pronounce it!” Juli Shamash laughs.  “My husband’s family are Jewish Iraqis. Some of them say sha-MOSH, but I say SHA-mish.” Indeed, at a recent committee hearing, Rep. Latta &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/live/X7rdmmwvQiY?si=1OmvhewBy_Cdu5W3&amp;amp;t=13001"&gt;mispronounced the name as sha-MOOTH&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Another element complicating things: this isn’t even the only Tyler’s Law recently introduced in Congress.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In 2024, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/nancy_mace/456843"&gt;Rep. Nancy Mace (R-SC1)&lt;/a&gt; introduced an identically-named but completely distinct bill named after &lt;a href="https://mace.house.gov/media/press-releases/representative-nancy-mace-introduces-tylers-law-protect-children-dangerous"&gt;10-month-old Tyler Jonathan&lt;/a&gt;, who died from a defective crib. The bill would have required reporting incidents of child deaths because of unsafe products to the CPSC (Consumer Product Safety Commission), but attracted zero cosponsors and never received a committee vote.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When GovTrack brought it up with Shamash, she replied, “That’s the first I’m hearing about this.” But she added that it reminded her of a story about yet &lt;em&gt;another&lt;/em&gt; Tyler’s Law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180AB295"&gt;A 2017 California state law&lt;/a&gt; increasing safety regulations on the skydiving industry. That Tyler’s Law was named after 18-year-old Tyler Turner, who &lt;a href="https://abc30.com/new-law-signed-in-memory-of-los-banos-teen-killed-in-skydiving-accident/2454847/"&gt;died in a skydiving accident&lt;/a&gt;. “A Pennsylvania state senator’s legislative director was researching a bill about parachuting. During his research, he actually discovered &lt;em&gt;our&lt;/em&gt; bill and signed on,” Shamash tells.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;What supporters say&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Supporters argue that Tyler’s Law can save lives amid a nationwide epidemic.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Fentanyl is the leading cause of drug overdoses in the U.S. and hospitals must test for it,” &lt;a href="https://lieu.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-lieu-introduces-bipartisan-bill-prevent-fentanyl-overdoses"&gt;Rep. Lieu said in a press release&lt;/a&gt;. “It is shocking that some hospitals do not include fentanyl testing for patients experiencing an overdose, [but] many physicians may not even be aware that the routine tests they run do &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; detect fentanyl. I have been honored to work with Tyler’s mom, Juli, on this bipartisan legislation to ensure no other family experiences such a devastating tragedy.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Too many families in Indiana and across America have lost loved ones to fentanyl poisoning,” &lt;a href="https://www.banks.senate.gov/press-releases/senators-banks-padilla-introduce-bipartisan-tylers-law-to-fight-fentanyl-crisis/"&gt;Sen. Banks said in a separate press release&lt;/a&gt;. “Tyler’s Law will help prevent these tragedies by directing emergency rooms to screen for fentanyl, ensuring overdose victims receive timely, life-saving care. I thank Tyler’s mother, Juli, for championing this legislation to make fentanyl testing a national standard.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;What opponents say&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;When the Pennsylvania House passed their version by 166-37, that didn’t break down neatly along partisan lines, as the 37 holdouts comprised 31 Republicans and six Democrats. In a state health committee hearing, two of them from opposing parties offered differing reasons for their mutual opposition.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the Republican side:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It’s well-intentioned, but misguided,” &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/live/KyY9bKTw5ng?si=oN8B4gW6QOA6lSdF&amp;amp;t=445"&gt;State Rep. Tim Twardzik (R) said&lt;/a&gt;. “I spoke to a hospital I’m affiliated with, and it doesn’t really seem to solve much of a problem. It adds costs to the hospital… It’s a good idea, a bad implementation.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the Democratic side:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“The language of this bill does not protect people who will be tested from this information being used as a punitive tool, instead of a treatment tool,” &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/live/KyY9bKTw5ng?si=2Jugy-SZSKWy_ecV&amp;amp;t=704"&gt;State Rep. Tarik Khan (D) said&lt;/a&gt;. “People who are already battling substance use are now going to be hit with more severe penalties. Because, in addition to perhaps cocaine, they’re also testing positive for fentanyl – which we know is being used to adulterate these substances, [often] unbeknownst to the people who are consuming them.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Shamash herself acknowledged some concerns in her own home state.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Although it passed California unanimously, “the California Hospital Association was concerned that their underreporting rural hospitals wouldn’t be able to perform the tests,” Shamash recalls. “But a few doctors, led by &lt;a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/roneet-lev-6189a0ab"&gt;Roneet Lev&lt;/a&gt; [former Chief Medical Officer at the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy] offered to help teach rural hospitals.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;What’s next&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Shamash plans to keep lobbying both at the state and congressional levels. She got some “inside D.C.” help in scheduling meetings this time around by connecting with Richard Mereu, chief government relations officer for the Emergency Nurses Association.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“The biggest surprise – and it is a pleasant surprise – is the level of interest and support for Tyler’s Law among senators and representatives, or their staff members,” Mereu tells GovTrack by email. “Certainly, having Juli and other mothers who have lost children to fentanyl tell their own stories has a huge impact in congressional meetings and highlights in a powerful way the need for the passage of Tyler’s Law.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Of all the Senate offices Shamash or Mereu contacted ahead of a recent February visit to D.C., only four agreed to meet with her and her fellow advocates in person. They represented an even mix of two Democrats and two Republicans: Sens. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/jim_banks/412702"&gt;Jim Banks (R-IN)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/timothy_kaine/412582"&gt;Tim Kaine (D-VA)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/christopher_murphy/412194"&gt;Chris Murphy (D-CT)&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/tim_scott/412471"&gt;Rick Scott (R-FL)&lt;/a&gt; – although neither Sens. Kaine nor Murphy have actually signed on yet.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No staffer wants to be rude, so they’ll say: ‘I’ll bring it up with my boss’ even though they usually don’t,” Shamash reports. “Only one person actually said: ‘My boss isn’t interested.’ Everybody else &lt;em&gt;acts&lt;/em&gt; receptive.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But the real answer might not be legislative, but rather to solve the problem at its source: successfully getting people to stop consuming fentanyl in the first place. Shamash travels the country giving talks about the dangers of fentanyl and other drugs to school groups, parent groups, student groups, young professional groups.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I take out billboards and bus ads. One of the campaigns says: ‘One line, one pill, fentanyl kills,’” Shamash says. “The DEA has a campaign that says ‘one pill could kill,’ but people still do cocaine! So I added the phrase ‘one line,’ because I want people to know that cocaine can be laced with fentanyl.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her two surviving children, a 28-year-old California education lawyer named Alexandra and a 22-year-old Atlanta investment manager named Griffin, plus her husband Charles, a bankruptcy attorney, help with the cause at their &lt;a href="https://www.drugawarenessfoundation.org/"&gt;Drug Awareness Foundation&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;Success&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;For now, Shamash can rest a little easier knowing that her efforts have already saved lives.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In 2024, Lauren Hinton of Garden Grove, California rushed her five-month-old son to a children’s hospital emergency room after he wouldn’t stop choking on his own saliva. Due to Tyler’s Law, the hospital was required to test her son for fentanyl, which was detected in his system. (Both parents were addicted themselves, but didn’t realize trace amounts of the substance could be passed to their children.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The positive test result made California authorities perform a welfare check on the home, where they found the baby’s twin brother &lt;em&gt;also&lt;/em&gt; had fentanyl in his system. Both parents were arrested, sent to jail, and forced into a monthslong rehabilitation program, while the twins were placed in foster care.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Since reunited with their children, the parents &lt;a href="https://www.scrippsnews.com/us-news/scripps-news-investigates/poisoned-fentanyls-child-victims/twin-babies-and-parents-saved-following-hospital-fentanyl-test"&gt;credit the state law with saving both of their sons’ lives&lt;/a&gt;. “Without that, [at least] one of them would have died,” Hinton, the mother, told Scripps News. “They wouldn’t be here… and neither would I.”&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Analysis and Commentary</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Bills on the Floor; Spending Negotiations Elsewhere</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/498/2025-05-05_bills-on-the-floor-spending-negotiations-elsewhere</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/498/2025-05-05_bills-on-the-floor-spending-negotiations-elsewhere</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 05 May 2025 16:53:40 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Good morning, GovTrackers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House of Representatives is &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;in session this week&lt;/a&gt;, with votes scheduled on twelve fast-track (“suspension”) bills as early as 6:30 p.m. Monday. These bills, which require two-thirds support to pass, largely focus on foreign affairs — Falun Gong, Taiwan, Iran, foreign influence, and the creation of a “Quad Inter-Parliamentary Working Group,” with the “quad” referring to the U.S., Australia, India, and Japan.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Two additional bills will be considered under a rule, meaning they require only a simple majority to pass. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr276"&gt;H.R. 276&lt;/a&gt;, introduced by Rep. Greene, would rename the Gulf of Mexico as the “Gulf of America” in federal government documents and maps. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr881"&gt;H.R. 881&lt;/a&gt;, introduced by Rep. Pfluger, targets universities affiliated with Confucius Institutes — cultural exchange programs backed by the Chinese government — by restricting federal funding to schools that maintain such ties, per a &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=4501"&gt;press release&lt;/a&gt; from House Republicans.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Much of the substantive work will occur in the &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/05/05?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22House%22%7D"&gt;31 House committee meetings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled this week. These include nine Appropriations Committee meetings as lawmakers work to advance this year’s spending bills — expect cabinet officials to testify. The Armed Services Committee is also busy, holding five meetings as it moves forward on the National Defense Authorization Act, a major yearly “must-pass” defense policy and spending bill. Other committee business includes anti-transgender hearings on, in the House Republicans’ phrasing, “keeping men out of women’s sports.” As discussed last week, the broader tension remains over how House Republican leaders will navigate &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/crs_external_products/R/PDF/R48444/R48444.3.pdf"&gt;budget reconciliation legislation&lt;/a&gt; and also the expected rescissions package, both expected to make major changes to federal spending.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate reconvenes today at 3 p.m. According to the &lt;a href="https://www.dailypress.senate.gov/monday-may-5-2025/"&gt;Senate Press Gallery&lt;/a&gt;, it will first consider a joint resolution to overturn an EPA rule on air emission standards related to rubber tires, followed by a vote on the nomination of Frank Bisignano to serve as Commissioner of the Social Security Administration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Seventeen &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/05/05?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22Senate%22%7D"&gt;Senate committee meetings&lt;/a&gt; are scheduled for the week. Appropriators are holding the most, with four hearings as they begin shaping this year’s spending bills. The Commerce, Science, and Transportation Committee follows with three. The rest of the committees have one or two meetings apiece. Seven of the hearings are focused on nominations.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Avoiding as Much Controversy as Possible for Now</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/497/2025-05-02_avoiding-as-much-controversy-as-possible-for-now</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/497/2025-05-02_avoiding-as-much-controversy-as-possible-for-now</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 02 May 2025 15:04:40 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week the House and Senate kept a relatively low profile.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House passed some non-controversial (well, within the House anyway in one case) bills, some non-controversial (within the Republican majority) bills beginning the process of cancelling regulations and snuck in a change to House rules via a resolution on rules for debate on some specific bills (again).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate, as usual in its Tuesday-Thursday week, confirmed a few nominees, completed the cancellation of a few regulations and almost passed a resolution that would have limited the upcoming tariffs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Regular House Bills&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;With the exception of the first one listed below, these bills are still early in the legislative process. They must next pass in the Senate before they can become law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s146"&gt;S. 146: TAKE IT DOWN Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h104"&gt;409-2&lt;/a&gt;. It will go to the President next for signing and become law. While it has been uncontroversial in Congress, there are considerable objections outside of Congress. Ostensibly, the soon-to-be law will provide punishment for the use of non-consensual intimate images online. However, as &lt;a href="https://www.techdirt.com/2025/04/28/congress-moving-forward-on-unconstitutional-take-it-down-act/"&gt;TechDirt&lt;/a&gt; notes "Instead of building on existing successful systems, or within the parameters of the First Amendment, Congress decided to create a new framework combining vague “duty of care” requirements with harsh criminal penalties — a combination that, as we’ve previously detailed, practically begs to be weaponized for censorship."&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr859"&gt;H.R. 859: Informing Consumers about Smart Devices Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would require the disclosure of a camera or recording capability in certain internet-connected devices, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h109"&gt;415-9&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1402"&gt;H.R. 1402: TICKET Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would require sellers of event tickets to disclose comprehensive information to consumers about ticket prices and related fees, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h107"&gt;409-15&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1442"&gt;H.R. 1442: Youth Poisoning Protection Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would ban the sale of products with a high concentration of sodium nitrite to individuals, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h108"&gt;378-42&lt;/a&gt;. We wrote about a &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s2233/summary"&gt;previous version of this bill&lt;/a&gt; in 2023.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr973"&gt;H.R. 973: Setting Consumer Standards for Lithium-Ion Batteries Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would establish standards for lithium-ion batteries, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h103"&gt;365-42&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;House Regulation Cancellations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;These bills are early in the legislative process. They must next pass in the Senate before they can become law.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres60"&gt;H.J.Res. 60:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the National Park Service relating to “Glen Canyon National Recreation Area: Motor Vehicles” passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h110"&gt;219-205&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h113"&gt;H.J.Res. 78:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service relating to "Endangered and Threatened Wildlife and Plants; Endangered Species Status for the San Francisco Bay-Delta Distinct Population Segment of the Longfin Smelt" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h113"&gt;216-195&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres87"&gt;H.J.Res. 87&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres88"&gt;H.J.Res. 88&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres89"&gt;H.J.Res. 89&lt;/a&gt;; all resolutions disapproving of waivers the Biden Administration gave to California to have stricter environmental rules, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h111"&gt;231-191&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h114"&gt;264-194&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h112"&gt;225-196&lt;/a&gt;, respectively. These may not come up for a vote in the Senate since &lt;a href="https://www.axios.com/2025/05/01/senate-gop-parliamentarian-ev-mandate-california"&gt;the Senate Parliamentarian agreed with the General Accountability Office that "waivers" are not regulations&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;No Investigations for Democrats&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;In what is becoming a go-to move for Speaker Johnson, a change to House Rules was added to the rules for debate for specific bills this week. This time, &lt;a href="https://www.huffpost.com/entry/adam-smith-pete-hegseth-signal-probe_n_6813834ee4b03d2b311bef2b"&gt;the rules change precludes Democrats from being able to force investigations into the current administration&lt;/a&gt;. Previous rules changes &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/493/2025-04-11_moving-forward-on-republican-priorities"&gt;preclude the House from using the primary method to cancel the President's tariffs&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/493/2025-04-11_moving-forward-on-republican-priorities"&gt;to force Rep. Luna to back down&lt;/a&gt; from an effort to allow proxy voting for new parents.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/493/2025-04-11_moving-forward-on-republican-priorities"&gt;H.Res. 354&lt;/a&gt;. This was a procedural resolution with an incredibly long title; the link goes to the specific clause that changed the rules.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Senate Regulation Cancellations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The first two bills will become law which is to say the referenced regulations will be cancelled. The next step will be for the President to sign them. The third though, still has to pass in the House, so it's early in the process.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres42"&gt;H.J.Res. 42:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Department of Energy relating to "Energy Conservation Program for Appliance Standards: Certification Requirements, Labeling Requirements, and Enforcement Provisions for Certain Consumer Products and Commercial Equipment" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s223"&gt;52-46&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres75"&gt;H.J.Res. 75:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy, Department of Energy relating to "Energy Conservation Program: Energy Conservation Standards for Commercial Refrigerators, Freezers, and Refrigerator-Freezers" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s228"&gt;52-45&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres31"&gt;S.J.Res. 31:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Environmental Protection Agency relating to "Review of Final Rule Reclassification of Major Sources as Area Sources Under Section 112 of the Clean Air Act" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s229"&gt;52-46&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;The Tariff Resolution, or The Importance of Being There&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;If Sens. McConnell and Whitehouse had been on the floor and voted the way they were expected to, this resolution would have passed. However, the Senate does not allow any kind of remote voting outside of committees. The resolution still would have had to get through the House, but now that will not happen.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres49"&gt;S.J.Res. 49: A joint resolution terminating the national emergency declared to impose global tariffs&lt;/a&gt; failed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s225"&gt;49-49&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Update, 5/7/2025: Originally we erroneously listed Sen. Van Hollen as one of the two Senators who missed the vote on tariffs when it was actually Sen. Whitehouse who missed it. We regret the error.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Recissions 101</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/496/2025-04-30_recissions-101</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/496/2025-04-30_recissions-101</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 30 Apr 2025 16:05:29 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;h2&gt;The Story So Far&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Since January 20, the Trump Administration has been cutting federal spending. The thing is that, once Congress appropriates funds and the President signs those appropriations into law (which President Trump &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1968"&gt;did on March 15&lt;/a&gt;), the Executive Branch can’t just refuse to spend the funds. Such a refusal is called impoundment, and there’s &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/R48432.html"&gt;a law to prevent it&lt;/a&gt;. Now the Trump Administration may seek to make those cuts legal through a process that can’t be blocked by the Senate filibuster.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On April 14, the &lt;a href="https://nypost.com/2025/04/14/us-news/white-house-sends-congress-plan-to-ax-all-public-broadcasting-funds-and-codify-doge-aid-cuts/"&gt;New York Post reported&lt;/a&gt; that the Trump Administration will make a “rescission request” to Congress to permanently decrease funding to the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, which &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RS22168.html"&gt;funds a small portion of&lt;/a&gt; PBS on TV and NPR on the radio, USAID, and a few other agencies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Impoundment Control Act of 1974, passed after President Nixon made several attempts to control policy by refusing to spend appropriated funds, codifies that the appropriations power — how much agencies are to spend — belongs to Congress and &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; the President, as the Constitution says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No officer or employee of the United States may defer any budget authority” (&lt;a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/2/684#b"&gt;2 U.S. Code § 684(b)&lt;/a&gt;) &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are exceptions to Congress’s power over appropriations, of which one is rescission. The key to the exception, though, is that Congress must approve it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But so far the Trump Administration has bypassed Congress in its efforts to decrease the size of the federal government. Examples include requiring agencies cut their staff, refusing to authorize grant money that’s already been awarded, attempting to reorganize agencies, and in some cases like with &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2025/03/28/us/politics/usaid-trump-doge-cuts.html"&gt;USAID&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/03/31/nx-s1-5334415/doge-institute-of-museum-and-library-services"&gt;IMLS&lt;/a&gt;, all of these at once. Without a Congressionally-approved rescission, permanent cuts like this are illegal. (And that’s not even considering the separate laws that &lt;a href="https://www.justsecurity.org/107267/can-president-dissolve-usaid-by-executive-order/"&gt;require the existence of these agencies and their functions&lt;/a&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;One outcome of the Trump Administration’s impoundments has been a flood of lawsuits against the administration. The cases are all still winding through the legal system and there have been mixed results. For example, the takeover of the U.S. Institute of Peace has largely gone forward as described in this &lt;a href="https://www.wired.com/story/judge-approves-doge-usip-office-building/"&gt;Wired article&lt;/a&gt;. Included in the takeover was the firing of most of the staff and seizing the Institute’s building and all of its contents.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There hasn’t been any direct response from the Republicans in either chamber of Congress. As President Trump signed the Continuing Resolution into law last month that set federal spending levels for the rest of the fiscal year, he &lt;a href="https://www.foxnews.com/politics/scoop-trump-crafts-plan-cut-spending-without-congress-after-shutdown-averted"&gt;announced that he intended to ignore it and cut further&lt;/a&gt;. When the separate budget resolution passed, which sets spending/cutting targets for the coming Republican reconciliation bill, the last few House Republican holdouts were convinced to vote for it because &lt;a href="https://thehill.com/homenews/house/5241651-house-republicans-trump-budget-framework-vote/"&gt;they received assurances still more spending would be cut&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Impoundment Control Act has been &lt;a href="https://www.cbpp.org/research/federal-budget/faqs-on-impoundment-presidential-actions-are-constrained-by-long-standing"&gt;challenged in court&lt;/a&gt; multiple times. In particular, the Supreme Court upheld the principles of the Impoundment Act in &lt;a href="https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/420/35/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Train v. City of New York&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. In the 1990s, Congress gave President Clinton a line item veto: The President could issue vetoes for specific provisions inside legislation to cut spending directed by the legislation. But the Supreme Court found it unconstitutional in &lt;a href="https://www.oyez.org/cases/1997/97-1374"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Clinton v. City of New York&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. The Trump Administration may challenge the Impoundment Control Act again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;How Does a Rescission Request Work?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Administration writes the request and formally submits it to Congress. According to the New York Post, this one was to be submitted on April 28 when Congress returned from its last break. (We’d link to the text of the request, but it doesn’t appear to be publicly available yet on either Congressional or Executive sites.) &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;From April 28 (or when the request is formally received if it’s not that day), Congress has 45 days to pass the request in both chambers and send it to the President for signing. By focusing on entities strongly disfavored by Republicans like public broadcasting and radio and USAID, the package has a better chance of passing in the short time frame with only Republican votes. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Per the Impoundment Control Act, rescissions do not have to get past the 60-vote threshold for ending debate in the Senate (aka cloture/filibuster), so the Democrats have no way to prevent the rescission from getting the simple majority it needs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;What Happens to Appropriations in the future?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Republicans and Democrats in Congress will likely continue to work out appropriations deals each year to keep the federal government open, but now it will be on the assumption that the Trump Administration will make a rescission request to change that deal after the fact. Or perhaps the Administration will keep on violating the Impoundment Act, making Congress increasingly irrelevant.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Analysis and Commentary</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Decisions and Recissions</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/495/2025-04-28_decisions-and-recissions</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/495/2025-04-28_decisions-and-recissions</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 28 Apr 2025 15:43:01 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Good morning, GovTrackers —&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Congress is back after a two-week recess. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;strong&gt;House of Representatives&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House will &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;kick off the week&lt;/a&gt; with a batch of 6 p.m. Monday suspension votes — a tactic to force members back into town. Eighteen bills are on tap, each requiring a two-thirds vote to pass since being “on suspension” means they’re bypassing the regular rules process.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Among them:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A bill to award a &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr452"&gt;Congressional Gold Medal to the 1980 U.S. Olympic hockey team&lt;/a&gt; that defeated the Soviets (the "Miracle on Ice"), and&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;A bill to promote &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr617"&gt;music tourism across America&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;The rest of the week will focus on five resolutions targeting Biden-era regulations, including:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Rules &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres60"&gt;limiting car access in a national park&lt;/a&gt;,&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;California’s efforts to promote fuel-efficient cars and reduce emissions (H.J.Res. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres87"&gt;87&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres88"&gt;88&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres89"&gt;89&lt;/a&gt;), and&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Protections for &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres78"&gt;an endangered fish population in San Francisco Bay&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;You can &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=4491"&gt;read how Republican leadership explains their priorities for the week here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Also expected this week: a rescissions bill — legislation that cancels funding Congress already approved.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;President Trump is formally requesting $9.3 billion in rescissions. His request would freeze that money for up to 45 days unless Congress votes to approve the cuts. Targets reportedly include funding for the State Department, USAID, PBS, and NPR (&lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2025/04/14/white-house-to-send-congress-a-formal-request-to-nix-9-3b-for-pbs-state-department-00289543"&gt;according to &lt;em&gt;POLITICO&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;House committees have scheduled &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/04/28?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22House%22%7D"&gt;thirty-three meetings&lt;/a&gt; through Wednesday.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Behind the scenes, committees are scrambling to turn budget reconciliation instructions into actual bills. According to &lt;em&gt;NPR&lt;/em&gt;, the &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/04/05/g-s1-58281/senate-budget-resolution-reconciliation-trump"&gt;result&lt;/a&gt; could be about $3.3 trillion in deficit increases, fueled by massive tax cuts and more Pentagon spending. The Center for a Responsible Federal Budget is &lt;a href="https://www.crfb.org/blogs/2025-reconciliation-resources"&gt;tracking the evolving legislation&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;One big political hurdle: gigantic cuts to social safety-net programs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Senate&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate floor is an enigma, as usual.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Today, the chamber &lt;a href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/2025/04/11/schedule-for-pro-forma-sessions-and-monday-april-28-2025"&gt;returns&lt;/a&gt; to vote on David Perdue’s nomination to serve as Ambassador to China (Perdue is a former U.S. Senator from Georgia). Expect most of the Senate’s floor time this week to focus on nominations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;One major question: Will Senate Majority Leader Thune &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/newsletters/inside-congress/2025/04/28/markup-madness-begins-00312128"&gt;ignore the Senate parliamentarian&lt;/a&gt; and push forward resolutions under the Congressional Review Act to repeal Biden-era regulations giving California waivers to set stricter car emissions standards? The issue, according to the Politico article linked above, is that the parliamentarian “...recently ruled that this allowance doesn’t constitute a formal rule, so it would not be subject to reversal by lawmakers under the Congressional Review Act.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Senate committees have &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/04/28"&gt;twenty-three proceedings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled. At least ten concern pending nominations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Several closed hearings are planned on national security issues, and some committees are advancing legislation aimed at addressing antisemitism.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Quick note: Not all committee meetings are posted online. For example, a Tuesday hearing on &lt;a href="https://www.appropriations.senate.gov/hearings/a-review-of-the-fiscal-year-2026-budget-requests-for-the-congressional-budget-office-the-government-accountability-office-and-the-government-publishing-office"&gt;CBO, GAO, and GPO appropriations&lt;/a&gt; isn’t listed on Congress.gov or the &lt;a href="https://www.senate.gov/committees/hearings_meetings.htm"&gt;Senate committee calendar&lt;/a&gt; — so the schedules aren’t fully reliable.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Moving Forward on Republican Priorities</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/493/2025-04-11_moving-forward-on-republican-priorities</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/493/2025-04-11_moving-forward-on-republican-priorities</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 11 Apr 2025 15:50:50 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week the Senate confirmed more nominees for various positions in the Trump administration. Both chambers passed legislation nullifying regulations which means several will now go to the President for signing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House was fairly tumultuous this week. While a few bills passed unanimously, two very controversial bills barely made it. There was also a brief rebellion over the management of discharge petitions, acquiescence on tariffs and, ultimately, acquiescence to the Senate's budget resolution (step one in the reconciliation process).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Regulation Cancellations Soon to be Laws&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Each of these votes, some in the House, some in the Senate, represent the end of the legislative process. They will now become law. They go to the President for signing next.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres28"&gt;S.J.Res. 28&lt;/a&gt;: A joint resolution disapproving the rule submitted by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection relating to “Defining Larger Participants of a Market for General-Use Digital Consumer Payment Applications” passed the House &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h95"&gt;219-211&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres18"&gt;S.J.Res. 18&lt;/a&gt;: A joint resolution disapproving the rule submitted by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection relating to “Overdraft Lending: Very Large Financial Institutions” passed the House &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h96"&gt;217-211&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres20"&gt;H.J.Res. 20&lt;/a&gt;: Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Department of Energy relating to "Energy Conservation Program: Energy Conservation Standards for Consumer Gas-fired Instantaneous Water Heaters" passed the Senate &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s207"&gt;53-44&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Bills Passed in the House&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;These are bills that have completed the first part of the path to becoming law because they've passed the House. Next, they'll need to be voted on in the Senate. Typically, there's a considerable delay between passage in the House and the Senate because the Senate tends to work more slowly than the House.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1228"&gt;H.R. 1228: Prioritizing Veterans’ Survivors Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h99"&gt;424-0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1039"&gt;H.R. 1039: Clear Communication for Veterans Claims Act &lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h90"&gt;412-0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr586"&gt;H.R. 586: Vietnam Veterans Liver Fluke Cancer Study Act &lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h89"&gt;411-0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1526"&gt;H.R. 1526: NORRA of 2025&lt;/a&gt;, which would limit judges' ability to issue nationwide injunctions, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h98"&gt;219-213&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr22"&gt;H.R. 22: SAVE Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would require proof of citizenship in order to register to vote in federal elections, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h102"&gt;220-208&lt;/a&gt;. This bill, which is based on &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/article/noncitizens-voting-republicans-election-2024-immigration-09b86e6768f755fd875f3c51b0e8ea70"&gt;the false belief that non-citizens commonly vote&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/article/congress-save-act-citizenship-republicans-women-0c0ba9fd8e6a01cf144736490c71df21"&gt;will make it harder or even impossible for millions of citizens&lt;/a&gt; to register to vote if they don't have or can't get the correct documentation.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Discharge Petition on Parental Proxy Voting&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;You may recall that last week we wrote that Speaker Johnson shut down the House after losing a vote that would have prevented parental proxy voting for 12 weeks after the birth of a child.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Johnson, and Rep. Luna, the FL Republican who was a bill co-sponsor, were each under pressure to find a resolution in order to not hold up work on the budget resolution any further. Luna agreed to allow the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres294"&gt;resolution&lt;/a&gt; she had put forward to be tabled in favor of "vote pairing". Vote pairing is when one member from each party agrees to not vote on a bill to cancel each other out. This does not address any part of the resolution Luna had put forward to allow new parents to proxy vote. When the tabling language was added to a procedural vote for other bills, it passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h92"&gt;213-211&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Formally Giving Up Tariff Power&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;In another procedural vote this week, &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres313/text/eh#link=2&amp;amp;nearest=H1FD09CD2D75C425ABFFA90E2EEDECE04"&gt;the House agreed formally to give up most of its power over tariffs&lt;/a&gt; in a vote of &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h94"&gt;216-215&lt;/a&gt;. While only one method of taking control of tariffs was prohibited in this vote, functionally, the House gave it all up to the President.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Acquiescence on the Budget&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House agreed to the Senate's version of the budget resolution &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h100"&gt;216-214&lt;/a&gt;. The holdouts who ultimately voted for the resolution describe themselves as "budget hawks" and opponents of increased budget deficits. Yet, they voted for a budget resolution that will increase the deficit anywhere from &lt;a href="https://bipartisanpolicy.org/explainer/whats-in-the-fy2025-senate-budget-resolution/"&gt;2 to 5.7 trillion dollars&lt;/a&gt;. They said they did so because "they received assurances from Johnson, Thune and the White House that significant spending cuts will be included in the final bill" according to &lt;a href="https://thehill.com/homenews/house/5241651-house-republicans-trump-budget-framework-vote/"&gt;The Hill&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;What Comes Next?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Now that the overall spending (or cutting, depending on your perspective) targets have been established, both chambers will have to decide how the money will actually be allocated. This will be the real fight and it will likely take months to get a final, votable budget reconciliation bill. Once that votable text exists, it can pass with a simple majority in both chambers and no Senate filibuster will get in the way.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>President Trump invokes emergency powers for new tariffs</title>
      <author>Chris Nehls       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/494/2025-04-07_president-trump-invokes-emergency-powers-for-new-tariffs</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/494/2025-04-07_president-trump-invokes-emergency-powers-for-new-tariffs</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 07 Apr 2025 16:31:40 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Thanks to the support from more than 1,000 GovTrack users, we are expanding our work beyond Congress to tracking the President and the White House, including executive orders. This is our first White House update that we're sending out to everyone. To get complete access to and support this new aspect of our work, you can &lt;a href="https://substack.govtrack.us/"&gt;subscribe here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr&gt; &lt;p&gt;In his April 2 &lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/04/regulating-imports-with-a-reciprocal-tariff-to-rectify-trade-practices-that-contribute-to-large-and-persistent-annual-united-states-goods-trade-deficits/"&gt;executive order on tariffs&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2025/02/fact-sheet-president-donald-j-trump-imposes-tariffs-on-imports-from-canada-mexico-and-china/"&gt;previous orders&lt;/a&gt; announcing tariffs on Chinese, Canadian, and Mexican imports, President Trump used the National Emergencies Act of 1976 (NEA) and the International Emergency Economic Powers Act (IEEPA) of 1977.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This raises two important questions: Do the National Emergencies Act and IEEPA allow the President to set tariffs, and is the current economic state actually an emergency? (We also covered some tariff history on &lt;a href="https://substack.govtrack.us/p/trump-invokes-emergency-powers-for"&gt;our full post here&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://substack.govtrack.us/p/trump-orders-tariffs-as-high-as-50"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; on the projected impact, Trump's rationale, and Congress's response.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Emergency and I: Who has the power to levy tariffs&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Congress — not the President — has the authority under Article I, Section 8 of the Constitution to &lt;a href="https://constitution.congress.gov/browse/essay/artI-S8-C1-1-1/ALDE_00013387/"&gt;create taxes including tariffs&lt;/a&gt; ("imposts") and the power to &lt;a href="https://constitution.congress.gov/browse/essay/artI-S8-C3-8-1/ALDE_00001057/"&gt;regulate trade with foreign countries&lt;/a&gt;. Over the 20th Century, however, Congress delegated considerable authority to set trade agreements to the President. &lt;strong&gt;But Trump didn't use these authorities:&lt;/strong&gt; He used powers granted to by Congress under national emergency law to set the April 2 tariffs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The National Emergencies Act created a formal process for the President t&lt;strong&gt;o declare a national emergency&lt;/strong&gt;, and IEEPA allows Executive Branch departments broad authority to &lt;a href="https://ofac.treasury.gov/sanctions-programs-and-country-information"&gt;sanction&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://ofac.treasury.gov/sanctions-programs-and-country-information/where-is-ofacs-country-list-what-countries-do-i-need-to-worry-about-in-terms-of-us-sanctions#:~:text=OFAC's%20Specially%20Designated%20Nationals%20and,names%20connected%20with%20sanctions%20targets."&gt;freeze assets&lt;/a&gt; of foreign actors once an emergency is declared.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;How trade policy fits under IEEPA is questionable. It actually was designed to &lt;em&gt;limit&lt;/em&gt; presidential power in the wake of the Vietnam War and Watergate, the law does not mention tariffs, and &lt;strong&gt;no other president has used the act to impose tariffs&lt;/strong&gt;, even as declarations of national emergencies under IEEPA have grown over recent decades. &lt;a href="https://www.lawfaremedia.org/article/the-case-against-ieepa-tariffs"&gt;Critics of the action argue&lt;/a&gt; that the only instance in case law that would support interpreting presidential tariff power under the act involved a temporary action taken by the Nixon Administration under the law IEEPA replaced.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;"The Constitution forbids it," &lt;a href="https://www.foxnews.com/politics/senate-approves-resolution-against-trumps-canada-tariffs-hours-after-liberation-day-event"&gt;said Republican Sen. Rand Paul&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; on emergency powers to set tariffs. And &lt;a href="https://nclalegal.org/press_release/ncla-sues-to-stop-trump-admin-from-imposing-emergency-tariffs-that-congress-never-authorized/"&gt;a lawsuit has been filed challenging it&lt;/a&gt;. (Also of note, a Senate bill to limit the President's power to set tariffs &lt;a href="https://bsky.app/profile/sahilkapur.bsky.social/post/3lma4eyocc22l"&gt;has seven Republican cosponsors&lt;/a&gt;, making it likely to pass the Senate, but it may be dead-on-arrival in the House.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Trump has used &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/crs-product/R48435"&gt;other trade powers&lt;/a&gt; previously. For example, Section 232 of the Trade Expansion Act of 1962 authorizes the President to raise tariff rates on goods the Department of Commerce determines are being imported in ways that threaten national security. Section 301 of the 1974 Trade Act allows the President to raise tariffs on goods the U.S. International Trade Commission finds are being imported at levels that harm domestic industry. It also allows the U.S. Trade Representative to impose tariffs on countries that harm U.S. commerce in "unjustifiable," "unreasonable," or "discriminatory" ways like failing to protect American firms' intellectual property or using child labor. The Trump Administration has cited these mechanisms in its rollout of several tariffs: It justified tariffs of 25% on &lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/03/adjusting-imports-of-automobiles-and-autombile-parts-into-the-united-states/"&gt;autos and auto parts&lt;/a&gt; from Canada and Mexico on March 26 under Section 301 of the Trade Act of 1974 and Section 232 of the Trade Expansion Act of 1962.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What exactly is the emergency?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The April 2 executive order includes its basis for declaring a national emergency:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Large and persistent annual U.S. goods trade deficits have led to the hollowing out of our manufacturing base; inhibited our ability to scale advanced domestic manufacturing capacity; undermined critical supply chains; and rendered our defense-industrial base dependent on foreign adversaries. . . . These conditions have given rise to the national emergency that this order is intended to abate and resolve."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The trade deficit is the amount the United States imports minus what it exports, and it has been &lt;a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/BOPGSTB/#"&gt;growing steadily for 30 years&lt;/a&gt;,&lt;/strong&gt; and especially since the COVID-19 pandemic began in Trump's first term. In other words, the United States imports far more goods than it exports. (A trade deficit in goods, which excludes the U.S.'s export of services, isn't necessarily a bad thing.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Congress passed the National Emergencies Act and IEEPA to enable the President to respond quickly to &lt;em&gt;swift-moving&lt;/em&gt; international crises potentially impacting national security. Compare that with the executive order's language that calls the trade deficit "persistent" 10 times (and "persistent decline in U.S. manufacturing output" once).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.justsecurity.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/IEEPA-House-Committee-on-International-Relations-report_1977-copy_clean.pdf"&gt;A 1977 House committee report&lt;/a&gt; on IEEPA stated any declared "emergency should be terminated in a timely manner when the factual state of emergency is over and not continued in effect for use in other circumstances." &lt;strong&gt;But despite the law's intentions, that's not how the law has been used in the past.&lt;/strong&gt; As this Congressional Research Service &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/crs-product/R45618"&gt;report notes&lt;/a&gt;, national emergencies can last indefinitely and the courts have rejected most challenges to the presidential authority under IEEPA:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;"As of January 15, 2024, Presidents had declared 69 national emergencies invoking IEEPA, &lt;strong&gt;39 of which are ongoing&lt;/strong&gt;. History shows that national emergencies invoking IEEPA &lt;strong&gt;often last nearly a decade&lt;/strong&gt;, although some have lasted significantly longer—the first state of emergency declared under the NEA and IEEPA, which was declared in response to the taking of U.S. embassy staff as hostages by Iran &lt;strong&gt;in 1979, is in its fifth decade&lt;/strong&gt;."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;The presidential definition of crisis also has broadened in recent years to include investment in Chinese industry and the international drug trade. President Trump &lt;a href="https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/research-reports/presidents-extraordinary-sanctions-powers"&gt;threatened&lt;/a&gt; to invoke IEEPA to levy tariffs on Mexico because of illegal immigration during his first term.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Courts are unlikely to weigh in on what is or isn't an emergency. Congress could end the practice of decades-long "emergencies," but it probably won't.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>The White House</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>House Stops; Senate Goes</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/492/2025-04-04_house-stops-senate-goes</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/492/2025-04-04_house-stops-senate-goes</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 04 Apr 2025 15:37:49 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week the House came to a halt early due to a standoff between &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/mike_johnson/412706"&gt;Speaker Johnson (R-LA4)&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/anna_luna/456891"&gt;Rep. Luna (R-FL13)&lt;/a&gt; after passing a few uncontroversial bills. You might think this means today's post will be short. However, &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt; the House did so little requires a bit of a long explanation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Despite a delay on Tuesday from &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/cory_booker/412598"&gt;Sen. Booker (D-NJ)&lt;/a&gt;, the Senate continued to confirm nominees and inch closer to passing a budget resolution of its own (step one in the reconciliation process).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Proxy Voting for New Parents&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/brittany_pettersen/456886"&gt;Rep. Pettersen (D-CO7)&lt;/a&gt; and Rep. Luna are the main co-sponsors of a &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres23"&gt;new House rule&lt;/a&gt; that would, if passed, allow new parents 12 weeks in which to designate a proxy for their votes while they're at home with their new child. Even though Pettersen is the main sponsor, because the majority is Republican and because she's been trying to get this rule passed in other ways, Rep. Luna has become the main face of the bill. The problem that Luna has faced is that Speaker Johnson claims any proxy voting system is unconstitutional.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;To get around Johnson's objections, Pettersen and Luna got 218 co-sponsors on their resolution. Reaching that number of sponsors meant that they could use the "discharge petition" process to force the bill to the floor for a vote.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Johnson, meanwhile, tried to use &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres282"&gt;a debate and voting rule on a set of other bills that Republicans support&lt;/a&gt; to prohibit the resolution from being brought to the floor for a vote. The rule &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h87"&gt;did not pass&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Quick House Procedure Note&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;The normal process for a bill to come to the floor is for the Rules Committee to set the time and amendment parameters for the bill. Once that's done, then the whole House either agrees or disagrees with these parameters. The committee can add additional content to a rule as well.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;It's rare, though much less so since last Congress, for the majority to vote against a rule. But with the vote margins in the House so narrow last Congress and this one, voting down rules has become a tool for small groups of members of the majority to express their dissatisfaction with leadership decisions.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When the rule failed, Johnson shut the House down. Why? Because if the House stayed in session, Rep. Luna or Pettersen could bring up the discharge petition which means that the resolution itself would need to be voted on within two legislative days (not the same as real days, but that doesn't matter for now). So until Johnson relents, the House is conducting no business.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;How might this standoff end? We don't know. There's talk about amending the resolution to specify it's only for 6 weeks instead of twelve and only for new mothers, but it's not clear that the existing resolution could be amended before it came up for a vote. Further complicating matters for Johnson, &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-speaker-mike-johnson-proxy-voting-congress-9e6de4d8629ce525641de2f27d4078dd"&gt;President Trump weighed in yesterday supporting the bill&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;For now though, unless either Johnson or Luna gives in or they find some kind of procedural compromise, the House is not in session. This means they are not available to work on the budget resolution that the Senate is in the process of passing right now. &lt;em&gt;That&lt;/em&gt; puts the reconciliation process further off and, like the Democrats when they last held the majority and the Presidency, reconciliation is pretty much the only way for Republicans to pass any of their priorities.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Sen. Booker Delays Senate Activity&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Starting Monday evening, Sen. Booker took control of the Senate floor and held it until 25 hours later on Tuesday. In so doing, he delayed some Senate business and beat Strom Thurmond's, a segregationist, old speech record. &lt;a href="https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/cory-bookers-26th-hour"&gt;Talking Points Memo&lt;/a&gt; covered the story and interviewed Booker about his goal with the speech.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Budget Reconciliation&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Now that the Senate is back to previously scheduled work, on Thursday, April 3, they passed a "&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s169"&gt;motion to proceed&lt;/a&gt;" on the budget resolution. This means the Senate is now debating the budget resolution. The resolution itself will &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/live-updates/2025/04/03/congress/senate-sets-up-final-budget-sprint-00270942"&gt;likely be voted on this weekend&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Assuming the resolution is passed this weekend, that means the ball is back in the House's court. (The Senate has passed a different version from the House's so the House has to vote again) Thus, there's considerable pressure on Johnson to resolve the Luna proxy voting issue as soon as possible.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Bill Votes&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;There were a few, including one that will be law shortly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres37"&gt;S.J.Res. 37:&lt;/a&gt; A joint resolution terminating the national emergency declared to impose duties on articles imported from Canada, which would end tariffs against Canada by ending the grounds on which they're imposed, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s160"&gt;51-48&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres24"&gt;H.J.Res. 24:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Department of Energy relating to “Energy Conservation Program: Energy Conservation Standards for Walk-In Coolers and Walk-In Freezers” passed the Senate &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s162"&gt;53-42&lt;/a&gt; and now goes to the President to sign.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr517"&gt;H.R. 517: Filing Relief for Natural Disasters Act&lt;/a&gt;, which extends deadlines for tax filing for people who have been in natural disasters, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h84"&gt;388-0&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr997"&gt;H.R. 997: National Taxpayer Advocate Enhancement Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h85"&gt;385-0&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1491"&gt;H.R. 1491: Disaster Related Extension of Deadlines Act&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h88"&gt;423-0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;See you all next week!&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Budget Reconciliation Progresses, Maybe</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/491/2025-03-31_budget-reconciliation-progresses-maybe</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/491/2025-03-31_budget-reconciliation-progresses-maybe</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Apr 2025 00:21:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hello Govtrackers, Congress will be very busy this week.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate may vote on terminating a presidential declaration of national emergency, according to the newspaper &lt;a href="https://rollcall.com/2025/03/31/this-week-senate-to-vote-on-tariff-emergency-ahead-of-possible-budget-vote-a-rama/?ref=com.devaary.cqrc.rollcall.v01"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Roll Call&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. According to a &lt;a href="https://www.kaine.senate.gov/press-releases/kaine-klobuchar-and-warner-announce-expected-vote-timing-on-their-bill-to-undo-canada-tariffs-that-will-raise-costs"&gt;press release&lt;/a&gt; from Sens. Kaine, Klobuchar, and Warner, the Senate is expected to vote Tuesday on &lt;a href="https://www.kaine.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/ros25392.pdf"&gt;this privileged resolution&lt;/a&gt; to “undo President Trump’s tariffs on Canadian goods.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate may also vote on a “compromise budget resolution,” &lt;a href="https://rollcall.com/2025/03/31/this-week-senate-to-vote-on-tariff-emergency-ahead-of-possible-budget-vote-a-rama/?ref=com.devaary.cqrc.rollcall.v01"&gt;according to &lt;em&gt;Roll Call&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, which could &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2025/03/30/senate-gop-to-start-moving-budget-plan-as-soon-as-wednesday-00259960?nname=inside-congress&amp;amp;nid=0000014f-1646-d88f-a1cf-5f46b4be0000&amp;amp;nrid=1a3f1abb-3676-4ca7-80a0-d93a12bb5910"&gt;happen as soon as Wednesday&lt;/a&gt;, according to &lt;em&gt;Politico&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Step one in the budget reconciliation process, the measure would provide directions to committees to draft legislation to change federal spending and taxation levels within certain guidelines. The guidelines are what are being negotiated.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The legislation the committees would approve would be combined into one big bill that would then be considered by both chambers of Congress. Crucially, such legislation would only need the support of 51 senators to pass, which means that it could pass with Republican support only.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The budget resolution to be voted on this week would take the form of an amendment to the previously-passed House resolution. We do not yet know what it would contain, but presumably it would include some senate priorities. The Senate had previously &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sconres7"&gt;passed its own budget resolution&lt;/a&gt;, but that is being set aside. The big political issue is whether Congress enacts one budget resolution containing much of Pres. Trump’s wish list, which is harder to do because it may contain provisions that some Republicans could not easily support, or to break it into two bills and pass the less controversial part first. Another issue is whether the legislation addresses raising or suspending the debt ceiling. On that point, the Congressional Budget Office said &lt;a href="https://www.cbo.gov/publication/60887"&gt;the government’s ability to borrow money&lt;/a&gt; will be exhausted by August or September.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House of Representatives largely will be waiting to see what happens in the Senate. The clock is ticking, as both chambers are in for the next two weeks, and then out for two weeks for the April recess.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;House floor this week&lt;/a&gt; are four bills that will be considered pursuant to a rule, which means they only need a majority to pass that chamber. Among those bills are one that would &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1526/text/rh"&gt;limit the ability of federal judges&lt;/a&gt; to stop the federal government from engaging in actions that may be unlawful and cause irreparable harm to people; another that would &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr22"&gt;make it harder for everyday Americans to register to vote&lt;/a&gt; by requiring a higher standard of proof that they are citizens; as well as &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s153"&gt;a resolution&lt;/a&gt; to disapprove of regulations that &lt;a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/final-rules/overdraft-lending-very-large-financial-institutions-final-rule/"&gt;protect consumers against overly large overdraft fees&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres28"&gt;a resolution&lt;/a&gt; to disapprove of regulations that allowed the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau &lt;a href="https://files.consumerfinance.gov/f/documents/cfpb_final-rule_general-use-digital-consumer-payment-applications_2024-11.pdf"&gt;to regulate some risks to consumers&lt;/a&gt;. Seven bills are on suspension, which means they require a 2/3s vote to pass the House. Most of them relate to taxes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/03/31"&gt;forty-eight committee meetings&lt;/a&gt; this week in the House and Senate. Some of them line up with the bills to be considered on the House and Senate floor, such as a House Judiciary Committee hearing on “judicial overreach” and a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing on the universal jurisdiction of judges. There are a handful of appropriations hearings, which address the levels at which the government should be funded, and there are a bunch of senate hearings on Trump’s nominees for various offices. We also see what appears to be the start of hearings relating to the National Defense Authorization Act, a major bill passed every year that controls the activities of the armed forces. The hearing that I am most excited about concerns funding for officers in the House of Representatives, which is probably less consequential than others but is related significantly to the operations of our Congress. I’ll be there in person.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Have a good week.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Legislation, Confirmations, Opposing Regulations</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/490/2025-03-28_legislation-confirmations-opposing-regulations</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/490/2025-03-28_legislation-confirmations-opposing-regulations</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 28 Mar 2025 13:51:59 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week the House passed a few bills, the Senate continued confirming Executive Branch nominees and both chambers voted against a variety of regulations established by the Biden Administration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House has &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; yet voted on &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s1077"&gt;S. 1077: District of Columbia Local Funds Act, 2025&lt;/a&gt; which would restore Washington, D.C.'s funding levels even though the Senate voted for it unanimously and &lt;a href="https://www.semafor.com/article/03/25/2025/dc-budget-fix-faces-slowing-momentum-in-congress"&gt;the White House has said it supports this bill&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House will also continue to include &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/elise_stefanik/412648"&gt;Rep. Stefanik (R-NY21)&lt;/a&gt;. She had been the nominee for the US Ambassador to the United Nations, but the Trump Administration has become worried about its extremely narrow margin in the House and &lt;a href="https://www.axios.com/2025/03/28/elise-stefanik-mike-johnson-trump-un-ambassador"&gt;withdrew her nomination&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Bills&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr359"&gt;H.R. 359: Cost-Share Accountability Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt;, which would amend the Energy Policy Act of 2005 to require reporting relating to certain cost-share requirements, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h72"&gt;405-0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1326"&gt;H.R. 1326: DOE and USDA Interagency Research Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would provide for Department of Energy and Department of Agriculture joint research and development activities such as grid modernization and security, rural technology development, and wildfire risks and prevention, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h73"&gt;372-35&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1534"&gt;H.R. 1534: IMPACT Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would provide for research and development of advanced technologies to improve the efficiency of cement, concrete, and asphalt production, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h74"&gt;350-73&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1048"&gt;H.R. 1048: DETERRENT Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would limit presumed foreign influence on US campuses by lowering reporting thresholds for gifts and requiring reporting of individual grants and contracts, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h83"&gt;241-169&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Confirmations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Among many confirmations of sub-cabinet level positions this week, these two are notable because of the importance of the FDA and NIH to the daily health of US residents. The Washington Post &lt;a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2025/03/25/bhattacharya-nih-director-cdc-makary/"&gt;wrote about both nominees&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Makary, Commissioner of Food and Drug Administration confirmed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s143"&gt;56-44&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Bhattacharya, Director of the National Institutes of Health confirmed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s141"&gt;53-47&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Opposing Regulations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The official information is all below, but to summarize, one or both chambers voted to let financial services companies continue to not report crypto sales, to keep appliances less efficient and to allow banks to charge customers as much as they want in fees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres25"&gt;H. J. Res. 25:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Internal Revenue Service relating to "Gross Proceeds Reporting by Brokers That Regularly Provide Services Effectuating Digital Asset Sales" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s151"&gt;70-28&lt;/a&gt; and goes to the President for signing next.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres24"&gt;H.J.Res. 24:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Department of Energy relating to “Energy Conservation Program: Energy Conservation Standards for Walk-In Coolers and Walk-In Freezers” passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h77"&gt;203-182&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres75"&gt;H.J.Res. 75:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy, Department of Energy relating to "Energy Conservation Program: Energy Conservation Standards for Commercial Refrigerators, Freezers, and Refrigerator-Freezers" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h78"&gt;214-193&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres18"&gt;S.J.Res. 18:&lt;/a&gt; A joint resolution disapproving the rule submitted by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection relating to “Overdraft Lending: Very Large Financial Institutions” passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s153"&gt;52-48&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Legislation and Hearings</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/489/2025-03-25_legislation-and-hearings</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/489/2025-03-25_legislation-and-hearings</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 25 Mar 2025 15:20:41 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hello Govtrackers, the House and Senate are back for a three-week sprint. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;House Republicans scheduled three measures subject to a rule, which means they need a simple majority to pass the chamber. Those measures include &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1048"&gt;the DETERRENT Act&lt;/a&gt;, prohibiting universities from entering into contacts with foreign entities without obtaining government permission and requiring disclosure of sources of foreign income; &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres75"&gt;H.J. Res.75&lt;/a&gt;, a resolution to nullify &lt;a href="https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2025/01/21/2025-00987/energy-conservation-program-energy-conservation-standards-and-test-procedures-for-certain-consumer"&gt;energy conservation standards&lt;/a&gt; for commercial refrigerators and freezers; and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres24"&gt;H.J. Res. 24&lt;/a&gt;, a resolution to nullify &lt;a href="https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2025/03/20/2025-04474/energy-conservation-program-energy-conservation-standards-for-walk-in-coolers-and-walk-in-freezers"&gt;energy conservation standards&lt;/a&gt; for walk-in coolers and freezers. Eight bills are on suspension, all of which relate to research in some way, and require a 2/3s vote for passage. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s1077"&gt;S. 1077, which reversed the cuts to Washington D.C.&lt;/a&gt; and passed by voice vote right after the continuing resolution was passed, is &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; on the list of bills to be voted on this week.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It isn’t on the calendar, but Rep. Luna’s &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres164"&gt;resolution&lt;/a&gt; to allow new parents to vote by proxy has received enough &lt;a href="https://clerk.house.gov/DischargePetition/2025031001"&gt;signatures&lt;/a&gt; to bypass the Rules committee and go to the floor for a vote. A rules change only needs to pass the House. We do not yet know when that will happen. In addition, Rep. Brandon Gill introduced a &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hres229"&gt;resolution&lt;/a&gt; to impeach Judge James Boasberg for issuing a ruling that Gill did not like on &lt;a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/texas/news/texas-congressman-brandon-gills-impeachment-articles-judge-james-boasberg-blocked-president-trump-mass-deportation/"&gt;the legality of mass deportations&lt;/a&gt;. A member can offer a privileged resolution to bring impeachment matters to a vote on the House floor.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate will continue to focus its floor time on confirming Trump’s nominees. You can see the queue of nominees &lt;a href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/2025/03/14/schedule-for-pro-formas-and-monday-march-24-2025"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/03/24"&gt;58 congressional meetings this week&lt;/a&gt;, with thirty-five in the House and twenty-three in the Senate.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Among the House hearings are a focus on &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/house-event/118057?s=1&amp;amp;r=9"&gt;reforming FEMA&lt;/a&gt;, an agency that Pres. Trump, at one time, said should be abolished. The House Oversight Committee is marking up a number of bills, including one allowing for the reorganization of the US government. The &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/house-event/118065?s=1&amp;amp;r=11"&gt;Judiciary Committee&lt;/a&gt; is focused on making guns and knives more widely available. House Natural Resources is holding a hearing that includes a &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr276"&gt;bill&lt;/a&gt; to rename the Gulf of Mexico as the Gulf of America. Legislative Branch Appropriations will &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/house-event/118041?s=1&amp;amp;r=19"&gt;hear from Capitol Police Chief Manger&lt;/a&gt; on that agency’s budget. The Intelligence Committee will hold its &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/house-event/118033?s=1&amp;amp;r=5"&gt;annual worldwide threats assessment hearing&lt;/a&gt; with the leaders of the intelligence agencies, just in time to discuss the Trump Administration’s use of a &lt;a href="https://www.cnn.com/2025/03/24/politics/yemen-strikes-journalist-cabinet-signal-chat/index.html"&gt;Signal group chat to communicate defense information&lt;/a&gt; about an upcoming bombing campaign. (The Senate has its hearing on the same &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/senate-event/336746?s=1&amp;amp;r=12"&gt;today, March 25&lt;/a&gt;.) And the heads of PBS and NPR will be hauled in for a hearing entitled “&lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/house-event/118051?s=1&amp;amp;r=8"&gt;anti-american airwaves&lt;/a&gt;.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate has a business meeting to vote to advance Mehmet Oz to run the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services; Foreign Relations will look at several ambassadorial nominations; Finance will hold a hearing on the nominee for Commissioner of the Social Security Administration; the Judiciary Committee will hold a very special hearing on the “&lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/119th-congress/senate-event/336745?s=1&amp;amp;r=22"&gt;censorship industrial complex&lt;/a&gt;”; and the bulk of the remainder are focused on other nominations.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the background of all this is &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2025/03/24/trump-agenda-stuck-congress-00242977?nname=inside-congress&amp;amp;nid=0000014f-1646-d88f-a1cf-5f46b4be0000&amp;amp;nrid=1a3f1abb-3676-4ca7-80a0-d93a12bb5910"&gt;Republican infighting&lt;/a&gt; over what to include in the budget reconciliation bill. This special measure can bypass the filibuster, and thus go to the president’s desk on a party line basis. Also of significant concern is &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/live-updates/2025/03/24/congress/debt-limit-x-date-july-october-congress-00244345"&gt;whether and how to address the debt ceiling&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Recent Republican policies and proposals limiting legal immigration and legal immigrants' benefits and rights</title>
      <author>Amy West and Joshua Tauberer       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/488/2025-03-23_recent-republican-policies-and-proposals-limiting-legal-immigration-and-legal-immigrants-benefits-and-rights</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/488/2025-03-23_recent-republican-policies-and-proposals-limiting-legal-immigration-and-legal-immigrants-benefits-and-rights</guid>
      <pubDate>Sun, 23 Mar 2025 14:23:52 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;In a &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/posts/478/2025-02-17_migrant-insider-repost-whos-shaping-immigration-policy-in-the-119th-congress"&gt;recent post&lt;/a&gt; we quoted a journalist describing the Republican Party as anti-immigration. Many of our readers wrote back angrily to say that the Republican party is only opposed to immigrants who are present &lt;em&gt;illegally&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But that's not true. And we're not shy of telling it like it is.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Recent Republican legislation and executive orders have sought to limit legal immigration, limit benefits for legal immigrants, and limit the rights of legal immigrants. Here are just some examples.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Limiting Legal Forms of Immigration&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Immigrants may currently apply for asylum  &lt;a href="https://www.uscis.gov/humanitarian/refugees-and-asylum/asylum/affirmative-asylum-frequently-asked-questions/questions-and-answers-affirmative-asylum-eligibility-and-applications"&gt;no matter how they enter&lt;/a&gt; the United States if they are &lt;a href="https://www.uscis.gov/humanitarian/refugees-and-asylum/asylum"&gt;seeking protection because they have suffered persecution or fear that they will suffer persecution&lt;/a&gt;. It's not unusual for &lt;a href="https://bipartisanpolicy.org/download/?file=/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Claiming-Asylum-at-and-between-Ports-of-Entry.pdf"&gt;asylum seekers to arrive between official ports of entry&lt;/a&gt;, look for Border Patrol agents and &lt;a href="https://www.uscis.gov/humanitarian/refugees-and-asylum/asylum"&gt;turn themselves in&lt;/a&gt; so that they can begin the asylum process. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr871"&gt;H.R. 871: RULES Act&lt;/a&gt; by Republican Rep. Anna Luna would make only entry at ports of entry an acceptable way to apply for asylum.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Trump Administration ended Temporary Protected Status for &lt;a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-administration-ends-temporary-immigration-program-venezuela/"&gt;350,000 Venezuelans&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.aclusocal.org/en/press-releases/tps-holders-challenge-shortening-humanitarian-relief-500000-haitians"&gt;500,000 Haitian&lt;/a&gt; who through designations during the Biden Administration were able to obtain work permits and deportation protection.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And on January 20, &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/article/trump-immigration-cbp-one-border-app-652854b5f2a4e6ccd6ee2ccc729cbb55"&gt;U.S. Customs and Border Protection announced it was shutting down the CBP One app&lt;/a&gt; causing thousands of people who were trying to enter the U.S. legally to lose their appointments.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are several ways to be born or become a citizen, but one is in the Constitution: The Constitution's 14th Amendment &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birthright_citizenship_in_the_United_States"&gt;reads&lt;/a&gt;, "All persons born ... in the United States, and subject to the jurisdiction thereof, are citizens of the United States." Now Republicans are trying to change &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birthright_citizenship_in_the_United_States"&gt;what "jurisdiction" means&lt;/a&gt;, contrary to the plain meaning of the word. On January 20, President Trump issued an executive order directing agencies to &lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/01/protecting-the-meaning-and-value-of-american-citizenship/"&gt;not "recognize" the citizenship&lt;/a&gt; of individuals born to parents either temporarily (e.g. with a visa) or unlawfully in the country, if they don't have citizenship another way. &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s304"&gt;S. 304: Birthright Citizenship Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt; and its &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr569"&gt;companion legislation in the House&lt;/a&gt;, introduced by Republicans, would do the same, and dozens of similar &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?congress=119&amp;amp;text=birthright%20citizenship#text=%22birthright+citizenship%22&amp;amp;sort=relevance&amp;amp;congress=__ALL__"&gt;bills have been introduced&lt;/a&gt; by Republicans over the last two decades. In unrelated but contradictory remarks, Trump's Secretary of Homeland Security &lt;a href="https://www.dhs.gov/news/2025/01/28/secretary-noem-delivers-welcome-remarks-dhs-staff"&gt;said of her department&lt;/a&gt;, "We have jurisdiction over people who live here, people who leave here, and people who come here. ... I tell people we have jurisdiction over everything."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Limiting Access to Benefits to Legal Immigrants&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;President Trump signed an &lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/03/designating-english-as-the-official-language-of-the-united-states/"&gt;executive order&lt;/a&gt; purporting to make English the official language of the country, though the president has no specific power to do so, and the executive order's only directive is merely that federal agencies &lt;a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/puerto-rico-worries-trump-english-official-language-rcna194249"&gt;won't provide language assistance&lt;/a&gt; to non-English speakers seeking federal services, which had been required since the 1990s. Around 15% of United States citizens &lt;a href="https://www.census.gov/library/publications/2022/acs/acs-50.html"&gt;speak a language other than English at home&lt;/a&gt;, as of course do many lawfully present immigrants (not to mention that in Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory inhabited by U.S. citizens, Spanish is the predominant language). Republicans have been &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/browse?congress=119&amp;amp;text=english%20official%20language#sort=relevance&amp;amp;congress=__ALL__"&gt;proposing bills in Congress&lt;/a&gt; to make English the official language for decades.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr746"&gt;H.R. 746: America First Act&lt;/a&gt; by Republican Reps. Jodey Arrington and Chip Roy would deny numerous federal benefits for health, child care and school meals, housing, and natural disasters to non-citizens and their children not only to those present unlawfully but also to those present legally through Temporary Protected Status and asylum. (It also would deny benefits to unlawful immigrants who themselves arrived in the country as children but now may be adults.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Limiting the Rights of Legal Immigrants&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;You've probably read about the &lt;a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/mahmoud-khalil-columbia-student-facing-deportation-palestinian-activis-rcna196799"&gt;detention of Mahmoud Khalil&lt;/a&gt;, a Columbia University student and lawful permanent resident (i.e. green card holder) who was born a Palenstinian refugee in Syria and led pro-Palestinian protests here. He's being detained with the intention of deportation. But he hasn't been charged with a crime. It's expected that the Trump Administration &lt;a href="https://www.stevevladeck.com/p/131-five-questions-about-the-khalil"&gt;will cite protest activities that would be protected by the First Amendment if he were a citizen&lt;/a&gt; but may not protect him from deportation. It's not clear how courts will rule on it. If they rule against Khalil, First Amendment rights will be significantly curtailed for immigrants.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Washington, D.C. municipal government and municipalities in California, Maryland and Vermont allow non-citizens to vote in local elections. It sounds odd today, but it was actually &lt;a href="https://ballotpedia.org/Laws_permitting_noncitizens_to_vote_in_the_United_States"&gt;normal for non-citizens to be permitted to vote&lt;/a&gt; through the early 20th Century. Republicans in Congress have &lt;a href="https://www.democracydocket.com/news-alerts/congressional-republicans-introduce-bill-to-ban-noncitizen-voting-in-d-c-elections/"&gt;sought to block D.C.'s municipal government&lt;/a&gt; from doing so.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Look, we know that politicians' have sometimes said that their goal is to remove incentives for illegal immigration. But we have always reported not on what politicians say but what they do. And what the policies in this article would do is limit legal immigration, reduce benefits for legal immigrants, and limit the rights of legal immigrants. And while obviously not all Republican officials have supported all of these policies, as a whole the party has clearly adopted an anti-immigration stance.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
